Welcome to notebook three of the Java track. The topic for this session is collections and generics. These two ideas go hand in hand. Collections are how Java represents groups of values. Lists, sets, maps, queues. Generics are how Java describes the type of element inside those groups, without forcing you to copy paste a separate class for every element type. You almost never see one without the other in real Java code, so we will learn them together.

Here is the map for what we will cover. The collection hierarchy and the four big families. List, set, queue, and map. The two main list implementations, namely array list and linked list, and when each is the right choice. The three flavours of set, hash set, tree set, and linked hash set, and how they differ in iteration order. The three flavours of map, hash map, tree map, and linked hash map. The deque interface and array deque as your default queue and stack. How to iterate properly, both with the enhanced for loop and with an explicit iterator. The immutable collection factories, List dot of, Set dot of, and Map dot of. Then generics. Why type parameters exist and what they buy you. How to write your own generic class and your own generic method. How to bound a type parameter with the extends keyword. Wildcards, both question mark extends T and question mark super T. The PECS mnemonic, producer extends, consumer super, which tells you which wildcard to use. And finally, type erasure, which is what the java virtual machine actually sees at runtime when your generic code runs.

Let us begin with the collection hierarchy. Java's collection framework lives in the package java util. At the top of the hierarchy is the Collection interface, parameterised with an element type E. Anything that holds elements implements Collection. From Collection branch three big families. The List interface, which is for ordered indexed sequences that allow duplicates. The Set interface, which is for groups that disallow duplicates. And the Queue interface, which is for first in first out ordered access. The Deque interface is a sub interface of Queue that allows access at both ends. Separate from Collection sits the Map interface, parameterised with a key type K and a value type V. A map associates keys with values rather than just holding elements.

Within each of these interfaces there are several implementations, each tuned for different performance trade offs. The interface tells you what you can do. The implementation tells you how fast each operation is and what the iteration order looks like. The standard practice is to declare your variable with the interface type and instantiate with the implementation type. That way you can swap implementations later without touching the calling code.

Let us look at lists. A list is ordered, indexed, and allows duplicates. The two implementations you will meet ninety nine percent of the time are array list and linked list. Array list is backed by a resizing array. Random access by index is constant time. Append at the end is amortised constant time, because the array doubles when it fills. Insertion or removal in the middle is linear time, because every element after the insertion point has to shift. Array list is your default choice. Linked list is a doubly linked list. Insertion and removal at either end is constant time. Random access is linear time because you have to walk the chain. Linked list is rarely the right choice in modern Java. For queue and stack workloads, use array deque instead, which is faster than linked list at every operation.

The list interface gives you the operations you would expect. The add method appends to the end. The get method takes an index and returns the element. The indexOf method searches for the first occurrence. The contains method checks membership. The set method replaces an element at an index. The remove method by index removes at that position and shifts. The remove method by value removes the first occurrence.

Now sets. A set holds elements with no duplicates. Adding a value that is already present is a no operation. The set stays the same size. The three set implementations differ in iteration order. Hash set is the default. Operations are constant time on average, and the iteration order is unspecified. You should not rely on it. Linked hash set has the same big O performance as hash set, but it iterates in insertion order. Use it when you want duplicate removal that preserves the order elements first appeared. Tree set keeps the elements in sorted order at all times. Operations are logarithmic time. Use it when you need a sorted set.

Maps follow the same three way pattern. A map stores key value pairs. The hash map is the default, with constant time operations on average and unspecified iteration order. The linked hash map preserves insertion order. The tree map keeps the keys sorted at all times.

The map interface has the operations you would expect. The put method assigns a value to a key. The get method looks up a value by key. The getOrDefault method returns a fallback value if the key is absent. The containsKey method checks for the key. Iterate over a map by calling key set, values, or entry set. The entry set gives you an iterable of map entries, each with a getKey method and a getValue method.

A few modern map helpers worth knowing. The put if absent method puts a value only if the key is not already present. The merge method takes a key, a default value, and a remapping function, and either inserts the default or applies the function to the existing value. The compute if absent method takes a key and a function, and if the key is absent, applies the function to compute the value to insert. These three methods replace a lot of get null check put code.

For queue and stack workloads, the right implementation in almost every case is array deque. Array deque implements both queue and deque, and it is faster than linked list for both use cases. There is also a class called Stack in the java util package, but that is a legacy synchronised class from the very first version of Java. Do not use it. Use array deque with the push, pop, and peek methods instead.

Since Java nine, every collection interface has static factory methods called of that return immutable instances. The static method List dot of returns an immutable list. The static method Set dot of returns an immutable set. The static method Map dot of returns an immutable map. These are the right shape for constants, configuration, and any collection you do not intend to modify. They are structurally immutable, so any attempt to add, remove, or replace throws an unsupported operation exception. They are also safe to share across threads, and they make defensive copying unnecessary.

There is one practical detail. The Map dot of method is only overloaded up to ten entries. For larger immutable maps, use Map dot ofEntries, which takes any number of Map dot entry instances.

Now, iteration. The enhanced for loop, often called the for each loop, is the idiomatic way to iterate any iterable. That includes every collection above and plain arrays. You write for, open paren, var name, colon collection, close paren, then the loop body. The loop variable is bound to each element in turn.

There is one subtle rule. You cannot modify a collection during an enhanced for loop over it. Doing so throws a concurrent modification exception at runtime. If you need to remove elements during iteration, use the explicit iterator object. Call the iterator method on the collection, then use hasNext and next to walk the collection, and call the iterator's remove method to safely remove the current element. If you need the index, fall back to the classic for loop with an integer counter.

Now we turn to generics. Notice that every collection above was declared with an angle bracket type, like List angle bracket String, or Map angle bracket String comma Integer. That angle bracket type is the generic type parameter. It is a placeholder filled in at each use site.

Generics give you two things at once. First, compile time type safety. The compiler stops you from adding an Integer to a List of String. Second, no casting at retrieval. The names dot get method already returns String, not the raw Object that you would then have to cast.

Before generics, in Java one point four and earlier, collections held raw Object references. Every retrieval needed an explicit cast, and the cast could fail at runtime with a class cast exception. Generics turn that runtime error into a compile time error. This is a huge ergonomic and safety win.

You can declare your own generic types. The syntax is to list type parameters in angle brackets after the class name. So a class Box of T has a single type parameter T. Inside the class body, you use T anywhere you would use a normal type. The field has type T. The constructor parameter has type T. The accessor returns T. When you instantiate, you pick a concrete type. New Box of Integer holds Integer. New Box of String holds String.

The diamond operator, which is just angle bracket angle bracket with nothing between, lets the compiler infer the type from context. If you write Box angle bracket Double pi Box equals new Box diamond of three point one four, the compiler infers Double from the variable declaration.

A method can also declare its own type parameter, independent of its enclosing class. The type parameter goes before the return type. So you write public static, angle bracket T, then T, then the method name. Inside the method, T refers to whatever type the caller substituted. The compiler infers it from the argument types at the call site. Generic methods are how you write reusable utility code, like a method that returns the first element of a list, or a method that inverts a map by swapping keys and values.

Sometimes you need a guarantee that the type parameter is a subtype of something specific. For example, you might want T to be any number type, so that you can call doubleValue on it. The syntax for that is bounded type parameters. You write angle bracket T extends Number. Now T can be Integer, Long, Double, or any other subclass of Number, but it cannot be String, because String is not a number. You can chain bounds with the ampersand operator. Angle bracket T extends Number ampersand Comparable of T means T must be both a Number and Comparable to itself.

Now here is where generics get subtle. Even though Integer extends Number, the type List of Integer is not a subtype of List of Number. Java generics are invariant by default. A method declared to take List of Number will not accept a List of Integer. This feels wrong at first, but it is correct. If List of Integer were assignable to List of Number, then inside the method you could call add and pass a Double, since Double is also a Number. Now your List of Integer would silently contain a Double, and the whole point of generics, compile time type safety, would be broken.

Wildcards let you opt into covariance or contravariance at the use site. The syntax question mark extends T is the covariant wildcard. It means a list of T, or any subtype of T. You can read T values out of a list declared with question mark extends T, but you cannot add anything, except null, because the compiler does not know the exact element type. This is why a method that only reads from a list should declare its parameter as List of question mark extends Number. That signature accepts List of Integer, List of Double, List of any other Number subtype, and it lets the implementation read T values safely.

The syntax question mark super T is the contravariant wildcard. It means a list of T, or any supertype of T. You can add T values to a list declared with question mark super T, but reading from it gives you Object, because the compiler cannot guarantee a more specific type. This is why a method that only writes into a list should declare its parameter as List of question mark super Integer. That signature accepts List of Integer, List of Number, List of Object, and it lets the implementation add Integer values safely.

The mnemonic for which wildcard to use was coined by Joshua Bloch in his book Effective Java. It is the acronym PECS, which stands for producer extends, consumer super. If a parameter produces values for you to consume, declare it question mark extends T. If a parameter consumes values that you provide, declare it question mark super T. If it does both, leave it as plain T with no wildcard. This is exactly the rule the java development kit uses. For example, look at Collections dot copy. The destination list consumes values, so it is List of question mark super T. The source list produces values, so it is List of question mark extends T.

The final topic is type erasure. Java generics are a compile time feature. At runtime, the type parameter is gone. The java virtual machine sees List of String and List of Integer as the same raw List. The type parameter is erased during compilation, replaced with its bound, or with Object if there is no bound. This is called type erasure.

Three practical consequences flow from erasure. First, you cannot write new T array of size ten. The java virtual machine does not know what T is at runtime, so it cannot allocate the array. Second, you cannot write instanceof List of String, because at runtime there is no parameterised list type. You write instanceof List of question mark, the unbounded wildcard, instead. Third, two methods that differ only in their type parameters compile to the same signature. So you cannot have one method that takes List of String and another that takes List of Integer with the same method name in the same class. The compiler sees them as duplicates.

Erasure exists for backwards compatibility. Old code that uses raw List and new code that uses List of String are the same List at the java virtual machine level, so they interoperate. The trade is that generics carry no runtime type information.

That wraps notebook three. You can now reach for the right collection for the job. You can define your own generic types. And you can read the wildcard signatures that pepper the java development kit's application programming interfaces. Notebook four turns these collections into the engine of modern Java. We will look at lambdas, at functional interfaces, and at the Stream application programming interface that lets you filter, map, and reduce your way through data, the same way Python comprehensions or Spark's resilient distributed dataset operators do. We will also meet Optional, the type safe alternative to null, which is how modern Java avoids the billion dollar mistake.
